Public procurement of building services and prevention of corruption
Joint report by the supreme control office of the Czech Republic (nkú) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
The award of services by contracting authorities is of great importance for both the state and the economy.
The state has the task of using public funds as economically and economically as possible and of ensuring fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure that competition is largely unrestricted across borders, contracting authorities have to comply with EU requirements for their contracts from certain value limits (threshold values).
To this end, EU Member States have to transpose and apply EU public procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.
The award of services is also an area at risk of corruption.
Because of the generally high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue advantages in the award of their contracts.
In January 2011, the supreme control office of the Czech Republic (nkú) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits for both the EU-wide award of construction services and the prevention of corruption.
The tests focused on the application of the EU public procurement law, which has been transposed into national legislation, as well as on the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in building construction, road construction and transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU thresholds have also been included in the considerations with regard to the prevention of corruption.
The audit results of both courts of auditors are summarised in this joint report.
The report should also be addressed to international bodies, such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
The evaluations of the Federal Court of Auditors on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional examinations, which he carried out in 2011 / 2012 with the building authorities, which are responsible for the road and building construction of the federal government in Germany.
He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and major construction projects.
In addition, the Federal Court of Auditors drew on results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluation of the audit findings from 2008 to 2011, which included construction measures in road construction, railway infrastructure, water construction, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.), as well as other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the awarding of federal public contracts is mainly carried out by the building authorities of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for awarding contracts in the area of transport infrastructure.
In the construction sector, the awarding of contracts is carried out in a decentralised manner by those who use the state budget.
In both countries, freelancers will also be involved in some of the procurement procedures.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.
Establishment of public procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures limited to the national area are governed by the budgetary law and the administrative provisions based on it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national awards, many additional individual regulations are provided for by internal administrative provisions,
Such as the so-called "Gaelic treatment books" of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in more detail in accordance with the jurisprudence of the public procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Public Procurement Act and other statutory provisions, which apply both above and below the EU thresholds.
The Public Procurement Law was significantly amended in 2012.
The new rules increased transparency in the use of public funds, allowed for greater competition and limited the scope for corruption in the award procedure.
Principles of public procurement law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiation procedure are to be applied in the case of EU-wide contracts.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are subject to the national types of award (public tender, limited tender, hands-free tender), which largely correspond to the above-mentioned EU-wide types of award.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (in the case of EU-wide contracts) and the public tender (in the case of national contracts).
In the open procedure and in the public tender procedure, any interested company can submit an offer.
Another essential feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized companies.
The main purpose of this is to divide an overall construction project into technical and partial ones.
The individual awarding of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the aforementioned features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.
More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are active in Germany.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable to construction projects below the EU threshold.
One exception is the simplified procedure, which allows a less stringent procedure to be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law, in accordance with EU law, provides for contracts to be concluded if competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between open and non-open procedures.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 are companies with 20 or more employees.
Volume of public contracts and shares of the types of contracts in both countries
In Germany, the total construction volume in 2011 was 307 billion euros.
Of this, 45.5 billion euros were spent on public construction (15%), which, in addition to federal construction, includes in particular the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.
The federal government's construction volume in building construction and road construction (excluding rail infrastructure and Hydraulic Engineering) amounted to 8.5 billion euros.
In 2011, the volume of contracts for construction services in the federal building and highway construction sector was distributed among the types of contracts as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public tenders, 12.7% open procedures and limited tenders, and 6.6% negotiated procedures and hands-on contracts.
Of these, 33.2% were Europe-wide contracts.
The volume of public works in the Czech Republic amounted to 4.7 billion euros in 2011, representing about 25% of the total volume of all construction projects in the Czech Republic.
In 2009, the volume was 7.8 billion euros, representing 37% of the total construction volume.
Breakdown by type of award for 2011: 65.1% open procedures 14.3% non-public procedures 9.5% negotiation procedures 8.4% simplified procedures for contract volume below the 2.7% threshold other procedures
The data refers to all public contracts for supplies, services and construction services awarded by public procurement agencies in 2011.
The above data shows that the parallel audits of both countries are aimed at a significant part of public contracts, which have a major financial impact on the prevention of corruption, which is to be observed in all contracts, and which have a prominent place in the award of contracts due to the open procedure and the public tender.
Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The supreme control office of the Czech Republic (nkú) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have conducted parallel audits in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and on corruption prevention.
In this context, the working groups of both audit bodies compared the corresponding legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of building construction and road construction.
In doing so, they noted in essence:
The EU directives on the award of construction services by public authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (Nos. 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, the prevention of corruption is also served by the procurement rules of both countries, which differ in their priorities and in their details (No. 3.2).
In both countries, a key requirement for procurement documents is that they must contain all the information needed to properly prepare bids.
The performance descriptions must be neutral and must not be subject to competitive restrictions.
In Germany, the Procurement Documents have largely complied with these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it is still a problem to determine the subject of the order sufficiently.
In Germany, building services are to be divided as much as possible into lots in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.
The ncú found during its tests, particularly in the field of road construction, that the awarding of large-scale services without lots or with very large lots can affect competition and result in a restriction to only a few large companies.
Narrowing of the market potential can lead to significant cost increases and risk price or other collusion.
Under the terms of both countries, the contracting authorities may, under certain conditions, agree in principle with the companies already commissioned additional or modified services that prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).
The respective requirements for determining the type of award were mostly followed in both countries.
Under the rules of the Czech Republic, the contracting authorities can choose between open and non-open procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary priority of the open procedure for EU-wide contracts or the public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national contracts, applies.
This will allow more companies to make offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, complicates price-fixing between bidders and leads to the most economic results.
In the case of construction projects whose estimated total order values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building authorities generally awarded construction services throughout Europe.
The correct estimate of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
In Germany, cost data banks are used for the cost calculations of public buildings, particularly in the construction sector,
Which are based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective instrument (No. 4.2).
In the case of construction services to be awarded throughout Europe, preliminary information and announcements must be published, which is intended to strengthen competition by enabling interested companies to prepare for the planned contracts at an early stage.
The audited building authorities generally complied with this requirement.
In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or lack of controls may have affected competition (point 4.3).
The selection of candidates for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of applicants invited must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be announced beforehand.
In addition to the requirements of the EU, the contracting authorities in both countries should change as often as possible among the companies to be requested when selecting applicants.
In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed specifications in Germany.
In some cases, the audited administrations did not take these requirements into account.
In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).
In both countries, in the interest of fair competition, it is necessary to ensure that companies interested in submitting bids receive the same information during the bidding phase.
In order to avoid anti-competitive collusion, contact between these companies and with freelancers involved in the preparation of the service description is to be avoided as far as possible.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
The audited building authorities in Germany did not comply with these requirements in part (No. 4.5).
When opening up the offers in both countries, particular attention must be paid to the multi-eyes principle and the principle of transparency.
The requirements for the labelling, documentation, storage and confidentiality of the offers are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly well defined in Germany.
The tests in both countries made few complaints (no. 4.6).
In both countries, the examination and evaluation of the offers are determined by guidelines for the organisation of the structure and the organisation of the agreements.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.
For example, contracting authorities handed over offers for testing to third parties without having to look through the offers beforehand and to document any anomalies sufficiently.
The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).
At the conclusion of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition will be informed of the intended contract before award.
This legal protection also has a preventive function against corrupt behaviour.
The Czech Republic also provides for a judicial review of non-EU procurement procedures.
Only in a few cases did the contracting authorities fail to comply with the specified deadlines or deviate from the bidders "offer in terms of content (No. 4.8).
The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible with the audited building authorities in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the award notices of some procedures.
Some of the shortcomings identified also reduced the anti-corruption function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).
Foundations of EU public procurement law and the prevention of corruption
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the award Coordination and the Remedies Directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the 8 Member States.
The general procurement principles of the European Union are, in particular, the competition law, the equal treatment law and the ban on discrimination, as well as the transparency requirement.
In order to achieve these objectives, the procurement coordination directive sets out specific rules for construction projects to be awarded throughout the EU.
In order to do so, their estimated order amounts must currently reach or exceed 5,000,000 Euros.
The rules relate in particular to the content of the procurement documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, including for the receipt of bids, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of the applicants and the Remedies Directive form the basis for the legal protection of the applicants and bidders.
In the event of possible infringements of public procurement law, the companies concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.
Prevention of corruption
The importance of preventing corruption
In both countries, there is no legal definition of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for private gain,
Which is usually prompted by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of the world's economic output.
For the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of contracting authorities, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may call into question the trust in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.
In doing so, they will have to review the structure and organisation of their administrations for areas that are particularly vulnerable to corruption, in order to make appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corruption-prone area of work.
Anti-corruption measures
In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery, as well as taking advantage of and approving benefits - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the federal government has issued a directive and recommendations on the Prevention of Corruption 12 in the federal administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following basic principles must be observed for the award area: priority of public tenders and open procedures, more-eyes principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, award and settlement, accurate and complete documentation of the award procedures.
In addition, other anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into public procurement legislation.
In 2011, for example, the Federal Ministry responsible for the award of contracts in the area of federal highways introduced an electronic control system,
With the gag data - such as the estimated costs and the order amounts - as well as information on the involved freelancers are collected and evaluated on a case-by-case basis.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of tenderers, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, are the most important foundations of the prevention of corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on the fight against corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended in it have already been transposed into national public procurement law and related administrative provisions 14.
The main provisions of the new legislation are: lowering the thresholds for smaller contracts, requiring the contracting authority to notify the tender in advance, including the reasons for the tender, prohibiting the restriction of the number of tenderers in non-open procedures and thus abolishing the possibility of selecting bidders by lottery, introducing the obligation to publish the contract documents and all the annexes, introducing the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Examination results on the individual stages of the award procedure
Procurement Documents
Procurement Documents the procurement documents must contain all the information that bidders need to make an appropriate bid.
In particular, the procurement documents must allow for an accurate calculation.
In doing so, bidders must not be given risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The Procurement Documents consist in particular of the performance description and the terms and conditions of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements to prove the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law for the Procurement Documents are in particular related to the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.
The performance description must be product-neutral.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the performance description is only permitted under strict conditions.
Avoiding restrictive requirements in the Procurement Documents is also a fundamental principle of the prevention of corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the procurement documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation in the preparation of bids and for manipulation of their valuation.
Regulations of German and Czech Public Procurement Law
Similar or similar regulations in both countries have been transposed into national law by EU legislation on technical specifications.
The services are, in principle, product-neutral without any factory specifications.
In the performance descriptions, the individual services must generally be subdivided into performance units with respective quantities.
The prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. euro per m ² or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the performance descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.
They must contain precise quantities and must not include services that do not determine whether they are needed.
Compensation based on flat rates or on time spent is to be avoided as far as possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on unspecified specifications in the Procurement Documents.
The service descriptions must enable bidders to prepare their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The tender will not be made public until the tender documents have been completed.
Diverging regulations
There is no obligation in the Czech Republic to tender for construction works in lots.
If it is possible according to the type of performance to be applied, the public procurement agencies can divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, building services are generally divided into lots, separated by the quantity (partial) and / or by type or subject (unskilled).
The aim is to enable small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, to expand the number of potential suppliers and to make price agreements more difficult.
This type of award is considered to be the most economical.
In the Czech Republic, evaluation criteria must be specified in the procurement documents, both in the EU-wide and in the national procedures.
The aim is to make it completely and conclusively clear to applicants which criteria are to be used to evaluate their offers.
In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the procurement documents, is only required in EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria are to be recorded only in an administrative award note.
Procurement documents drawn up by authorised professionals may not contain references to these offices or involved planners or surveyors in Germany from the civil engineering and some road construction administrations.
This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the knowledge of the client about contact with these freelancers.
This is also the reason why freelance procurement documents are not allowed to be sent out or to interpret planning documents for inspection.
The contact person for the companies is the client alone.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.
Additional or modified services, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements), are almost always required for large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions allow, to a certain extent, the award of subpoenas to the company already commissioned, without having to carry out a public procurement procedure.
In accordance with EU requirements and German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary services must not exceed half of the main contract.
In addition, the additional services cannot be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies to the award without a public announcement.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.
If additional services are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the Contractor is in principle not possible under the regulations in Germany.
In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis for determining the price of the order already placed must be taken as a starting point.
In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, small quantities cannot be charged with additional supplementary services.
Key test results
BHR
Technical specifications and product-neutral tender
In individual cases, the performance descriptions contained references to national technical approvals or standards that had already been replaced by pan-European standards.
Some performance descriptions also included product-related specifications - for example for graffiti protection, joint tapes or noise protection panels - without this being required.
In some cases, performance requirements were described in such detail that only one product was eligible.
Lists of services subdivided according to partial services
In none of the cases examined, the BRH has found breaches of the requirement to tender services in principle in a list of services subdivided by partial services.
Completeness of the service descriptions
In the vast majority of cases, the procurement documents were completed before the start of the tenders.
In some cases, the procurement documents had to be corrected during the tender phase, as positions or deadlines had changed in some cases.
In some cases, the performance indexes contained positions where it was not clear whether they were needed.
A list of services for demolition work even consisted almost half of such needs.
Lots and valuation criteria
For many of the awards, the prescribed reason for not dividing the Services, which were mostly advertised after the absence of specialists, into partial ones, was missing.
There were no complaints about the criteria to be used in the evaluation of the offers.
References to freelancers
A small part of the performance descriptions contained references to the freelancers involved.
Their names were partly on the cover pages or in accompanying plans or reports.
In one case, the awarding authority even explicitly asked the applicants to contact the architect "on questions of the tender."
In the construction sector in particular, the contracting authorities attributed the above-mentioned complaints mainly to the failings of the freelancers responsible for producing the performance descriptions.
The construction services pointed to the lack of capacity in order to be able to adequately control the performance descriptions.
Nkú
Technical specifications and product-neutral tender for the public procurement of the construction of a residential building with 12 residential units were specified in the performance description as a supplier and a specific product brand.
The contracting authority did not allow the use of comparable products without justifying this.
During the construction of several university buildings, suppliers and products were also specified in the tender.
Performance descriptions with performance units
In the case of construction projects in some industrial areas, the contracting authority did not clearly specify the scope and nature of the services required in the specifications.
As power units, it merely stated the converted space of the individual buildings in cubic metres.
Completeness of the service descriptions
In the course of the construction of a motorway bypass, the specifications of services were changed four times during the period from August to September 2009,
Since the scope of services had considerably increased and the technical requirements had changed.
Tender documents for social buildings included inaccurate location information, insufficient preliminary structural studies and incomplete design drawings, which required additional services.
When building a large library building, the performance description of the Interior did not include product quality requirements.
As a result of this lack of specifications, some subcontractors built overpriced and inappropriately high-quality equipment.
Lots and aptitude criteria
In the Czech Republic, the division of construction measures into partial lots or the award of partial contracts is not mandatory.
An examination of the three large sections of the construction of a motorway ring showed that, if selected parts were awarded separately, savings of up to 31.6 million euros would have been possible with a total cost of 620.3 million euros.
For example, six different buildings, which were the subject of a single contract, could have saved 2.5 million euros (25%) in a separate award.
If the construction of 20 bridges were to be awarded separately, savings of 11.5 million euros (25%) would have been possible compared to a total allocation.
When awarding construction services in road construction, the central contracting authority specified very extensive reference requirements as aptitude criteria.
In the construction of part of a motorway, the contracting authority required bidders in an open procedure to prove, among other things, at least three road construction projects carried out, worth 28 million euros each over the past five years.
In the Czech Republic, a maximum of nine providers met these requirements.
The public award of another section of a motorway included six separate construction projects, in which the contracting authority had specified an annual construction volume of at least 480 million euros over the past three years as a criterion of suitability for the companies.
Two thirds of the funds spent on road construction projects in 2008 and 2009 (i.e. 2.5 billion Euros out of a total of 3.7 billion Euros) were contracted by a total of five companies that carried out the contracts alone or as a working group.
In 46 procurement procedures with an order volume of 528 million euros, only two or even only one bidder made an offer.
The ncú showed that narrowing the market potential could lead to significant cost increases.
Additional services
In the construction of a motorway bypass, the contracting authority did not apply any of the procedures required by law when awarding additional services in two cases, nor did it enter into written contracts for the additional services.
Due to unclear quantity and quality specifications, supplements were generated in the first case of up to 63.7 million Euros (net) and in the second case up to 165.4 million Euros (net), which increased the respective order volume by 21% and 91% respectively.
