Other findings
On the basis of a sampling of construction projects, the nkú found that the average cost of building a four-lane motorway kilometre in the Czech Republic is up to 14.6 million euros.
In Germany, on the other hand, according to an analysis of long-term data from the Federal Ministry of Construction, the average cost of a four-lane motorway kilometre is up to 10.4 million euros.
This comparison suggests that motorway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take account of EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and the prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement for the sufficient certainty of the performance descriptions should enable bidders to calculate and draw up their offers in an appropriate manner,
Protect the client from additional services to be agreed upon subsequently and also limit the scope for speculation.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for the Procurement Documents are supplemented by regulations aimed at further reducing restrictions on competition and the possibility of manipulation.
In the Czech Republic, there are no requirements to this extent, but transparency is increased by the publication of the evaluation criteria in the non-EU procurement procedures.
The performance description requirements have been largely met in both countries.
In some cases, however, it was necessary to object to deviations that may have led to restrictions on competition.
The German Law on the formation of lots promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the ncú's audit findings, the award of large-scale services without loosely or with very large loose restrictions on the number of suppliers can result in only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements for road construction in the Czech Republic have meant that public contracts are awarded only to a narrow circle of suppliers and that smaller and medium-sized companies are not allowed to compete.
Also, a limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increases the risk of price or other collusion.
In the award and remuneration of additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches in both countries differ.
According to EU requirements and German regulations, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract can be awarded under certain conditions without public procurement procedures.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20%, up to which additional services can be awarded to the original contractor in the negotiation process without notice.
