This limit is often exceeded,
Because the scope of services for public contracts is often insufficiently defined.
If the excess is greater than 20%, the additional services must be advertised with public notice.
By dividing services into lots, restrictions on competition and the resulting adverse consequences can be avoided.
Determining the type of award and taking into account the EU threshold
By determining the type of award, the client determines the extent of the number of companies participating in the competition.
It can leave the circle of potential candidates and bidders largely uncapped, for example by choosing an open procedure, or by imposing non-public procurement procedures.
For construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, Europe-wide procurement procedures are to be applied.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
When choosing the type of award, the contracting authority must, in particular, take into account the European laws on competition and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of the construction services of a project is at or above the EU threshold of currently 5,000,000 Euros, the construction services are to be awarded throughout Europe in accordance with open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
In the case of construction projects that reach or exceed the EU threshold, the contracting authority may deviate to a limited extent from the principle of pan-European procurement and award works in national procurement contracts, provided that the estimated value of the respective lot is less than 1,000,000 euros and that the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total value of all construction contracts.
A uniform construction project must not be divided into individual measures without compelling reason or deliberately estimated at too low cost values in order to avoid the obligation to award construction services on a Europe-wide basis.
Since restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the type of award is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed justification of the chosen type of award, as well as the examination of the application of the EU procurement rules, are important elements of the documentation of the award procedure.
Regulations of German and Czech Public Procurement Law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed the EU rules on procurement procedures and the threshold into national law.
Diverging regulations
The Czech Republic has also transferred the fundamental equality of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU Directive to its construction contracts, which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and non-open proceedings, without the decision to grant or justify it. However, other proceedings are only possible under certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or, in the case of national awards, the public tender, as a matter of principle, takes precedence. This is laid down by budgetary and public procurement law as well as by the anti-corruption directives.
Other types of award - as well as the non-open procedure or the limited tendering procedure - are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated in the public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be substantiated and documented.
The principle of the primacy of the open procedure or the public tender is intended to ensure that competition is as unrestricted as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by the definition of certain bidders and to make possible price agreements between the bidders more difficult.
The principle of public tender is a central element in the prevention of corruption in Germany.
The correct estimate of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
The construction services in Germany can use planning and cost data banks of public administrations and other organisations to determine the expected costs in the area of public building construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost indicators for building categories, usage units, components or individual building services.
On the basis of such cost indicators, the expected order value of a planned project or a construction performance to be awarded can be determined.
Corresponding cost data banks for road construction have only a few building authorities in Germany.
However, a nationwide introduction for all Road Administration is planned.
Contracting authorities in the Czech Republic cannot rely on central databases or average price surveys of comparable construction measures to determine the estimated cost of construction services.
In most cases, the cost calculations are based on the estimates of the financing body or on the amount of the funds made available to the building services.
Measures to standardise cost-sharing procedures are still in their infancy.
