In a cross-sectional investigation, the BRH found, on the basis of more than 16,000 procurement procedures, that the non-public types of contracts have significant competitive disadvantages compared to open procedures and public tenders and increase the risk of manipulation and corruption.
In the construction sector, more than twice as many bids were submitted for public tenders as for limited tenders and almost three times as many bids as for hands-free tenders.
The investigation also found that, on average, BID prices were 6% and 10% higher for limited tenders and hands-free tenders than for public tenders.
Parallel investigations by the Federal Ministry of Construction and a State Court of Auditors confirmed the economic differences between public and non-public types of contracts.
As a result of its studies on economic efficiency, the Federal Ministry of Construction even found twice as many differences between public and non-public procurement procedures.
