For the construction projects for which they had calculated an estimated total contract value of more than 5,000,000 Euros, the audited contracting authorities usually drew up procurement plans in which they determined the construction works to be awarded according to EU and national procurement procedures.
According to the award plans, this meant that more than 80% of the construction work had to be awarded across the EU.
It was not possible to establish a circumvention of the obligation to spend on EU-wide contracts by means of cost estimates that were too low.
However, partly as a result of erroneous calculations, the minimum share of EU procurement procedures was actually lower.
During the construction, some contracting authorities improperly changed the stipulations of their procurement plans.
They did not justify these changes and did not demonstrate that the minimum share of EU-wide procurement procedures was still respected.
For most of the construction projects tested, the share of EU-wide tenders was usually lower than foreseen under the tender plan, according to the settlement results.
In some cases, in construction projects above the EU threshold, the contracting authorities breached the requirement to tender all 1,000,000 euros and more comprehensive individual lots in EU-wide procedures,
