In it, he has to make known, among other things, the scope of services, the process and execution dates, the special requirements as well as the evaluation criteria and their weighting.
The vocabulary of Common Procurement Vocabulary (CPV codes), which is standardised across Europe, must be used to describe the subject of the contract.
Preliminary information and notices will be published in the Official Journal of the European Union and in the buyer's profile.
In order to prevent discrimination against foreign interested parties, notices at national level must not contain any additional information and must not be published until the publication text has been sent to the Office for Official Publications of the European Union.
Incomplete or incorrect information in the notice may affect competition and may even support manipulation.
Regulations of German and Czech Public Procurement Law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully implemented the EU legal requirements for advance information and notice into national law.
Diverging regulations
In the Czech Republic, preliminary information and announcements are to be published, even in the case of construction works not to be awarded throughout Europe.
Procurement procedures may be started at the earliest one month after sending the preliminary information to the EU Official Journal (for EU-wide contracts) or to the National Official Journal (for all contracts).
Only in exceptional cases can the publication of a preliminary information be dispensed with.
In Germany, no prior information is required for non-EU procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, notices for public tenders and competitions must be published on the federal internet portal and, if necessary, in newspapers or magazines before restricted tenders.
In the case of restricted tenders without competition, announcements of the services to be awarded are required from 25,000 euros (ex ante transparency).
In the preliminary information, all planned lots of the construction projects are to be listed.
In Germany, this is of particular importance because of the smallness of the loose building contracts.
In the Czech Republic, this arrangement has only a small impact, as much less construction work is divided into lots.
