In Germany, in the case of limited tenders, at least three candidates must be invited to submit bids, and in the case of free-handed tenders, several suitable candidates must be invited to submit bids.
Under the new Czech rules, with the exception of two special areas, it is not permitted to restrict the number of bidders in the case of non-open procedures and negotiation procedures.
In Germany, the multi-eye principle must be observed when selecting companies.
For example, if an employee has proposed a number of companies for a non-public procurement procedure, the management level of the construction authority or an agent from the contracting authority will usually have to amend this proposal by removing, for example, a proposed company and / or adding a new company.
The aim is to prevent a single person from being able to determine the final circle of companies to be involved in the competition.
Otherwise, in the case of manipulative intentions, this could allow for wide-ranging collusion among the parties involved.
The list of companies to be requested is to be treated confidentially and not to be made generally accessible, even to freelancers.
