Opening up the offers
Opening up the offers
During the opening date, the previously closed offers will be opened and their contents will be read out and thus made public.
From the opening date, bidders will be bound by their bids until the deadline set by the contracting authority.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
There are no separate EU legal rules for opening up the offers.
However, the national rules on Corruption Prevention contain extensive provisions for the protection of offers and competition during this highly sensitive phase of the award procedure.
The multi-eyes principle, as well as the transparency and comprehensibility of the offer opening, are intended to prevent manipulation and changes in the submitted offers.
Regulations of German and Czech Public Procurement Law
The same or similar rules
The opening date is to be carried out by several persons to be appointed by the contracting authority.
The multi-eyes principle is designed to prevent individuals from manipulating the offers uncontrollably when opening the offers.
In most procurement procedures, bidders can take part in the opening date.
Only offers submitted to the head of the negotiations at the opening of the first offer are allowed for the opening.
Late bids must not be taken into account in principle.
In order to ensure the transparency of the opening date, the actions taken and the results of the opening of the offer must be recorded in a protocol, including the names of the bidders and the price of the offer.
The protocol is to be read out and signed by the head of the negotiations.
It can also be signed by the bidders present.
