Examination and evaluation of the offers
The examination and evaluation of the offers of the clients must examine and evaluate the offers available at the opening date.
In doing so, he has to determine the offer for the award of the award, which is best suited to the requirements according to the specified award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The EU's requirements provide for a multi-stage procedure:
First of all, the suitability of the bidders must be determined.
Bidders must be economically and financially viable and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
Companies that are legally convicted of bribery and fraud offences, for example, must in principle be excluded from participation in the award procedure.
The bids of the non-excluded bidders are to be examined mathematically, technically and economically and evaluated on the basis of the previously announced award criteria.
The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer. Offers with unusually low prices have to be examined by the client in particular.
The examination and evaluation of tenders is a particularly vulnerable phase of the award procedure.
For example, bidders can be unjustifiably excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements can remain in competition.
By favouring or discriminating against bidders, the value result can be impermissible and thus the determination of the economically most advantageous offer can be prevented.
The contracting authority must therefore make special arrangements to ensure that the persons responsible for the examination and evaluation meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure the transparency and comprehensibility of the procedure and the decisions taken.
Regulations of German and Czech Public Procurement Law
The same or similar rules
In line with EU requirements, the offers in both countries must be examined and evaluated in multi-stage procedures.
The requirements for the companies' aptitude certificates to be submitted, as well as the award criteria to be taken into account in the assessment and their weighting, are laid down in the notices or in the award documents and cannot be changed during the procedure.
After checking the suitability of the bidder, the suitability criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of the bids.
The score has to be limited to the award criteria.
The submitted offers must first be formally examined as to whether they are complete and whether, for example, they contain any anomalies that could indicate possible intentions of manipulation.
If bidders are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their bids, they must be informed immediately.
If the price of the offers appears to be inappropriately low, the bidder must be given the opportunity to comment before a possible exclusion of his offer.
The decisions made during the examination and evaluation of the offers must be documented in a comprehensible manner.
Diverging regulations
In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to persons directly involved in the processing.
Only the contracting authority is allowed to carry out the review of the offers as well as the calculation of the offers.
It will only employ staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of further testing and evaluation tasks is not regulated in more detail.
If freelancers are charged with the examination and evaluation, they must treat the Offers confidentially.
They are only allowed to make proposals for the decisions to be taken by the contracting authorities.
Procurement committees are to be set up in the Czech Republic to examine and evaluate bids.
The committees draw up evaluation reports with award proposals.
Ultimately, as in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the award of contracts.
If the documents or declarations required for submission of bids in Germany are only partially submitted, the contracting authority shall give the bidders the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the deadline, can the offer be excluded from the rating.
In the Czech Republic, it is up to the contracting authority to decide whether it will give bidders the opportunity to complete the missing documents or declarations.
If a bidder fails to do so, he must be excluded.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the uniform prices (prices for partial services) of the offers are to be examined.
If, due to the price structure of the offer, there are indications that prices for partial services are too low or too high, the bidder is to be asked to clarify these ambiguities.
If he fails to do so and the contracting authority can provide proof of a mixed calculation of the prices, this offer must be excluded.
This is to prevent Bidders from speculating on significant changes in the volume of partial services when calculating their bid, which can lead to significant increases in the cost of construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the appropriateness of the prices of partial services.
A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
A surcharge may not be awarded in Germany for offers with inappropriately high or low prices.
If one or more bids fall short of the true price determination of the client or the bid totals of the other bidders by 10% or more, the bidders must prove the correct calculation of their bids.
If they are not able to do so, the contracting authority can exclude the relevant offers.
In the Czech Republic, the tender can be cancelled after the economic assessment, if only offers with unjustifiable low prices are available.
In contrast to German public procurement law, for this reason, the contract cannot be refused for offers with prices considerably higher than the client's calculation.
If there is a suspicion of restrictive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority must immediately report to its supervisory authority.
The latter has to decide which measures to take and whether the antitrust authority or the public prosecutor's office should be informed.
For example, the competent authority at the top level must also agree on construction services of more than 50,000 euros if they are to be awarded on a hands-free basis, if a contract is not awarded on the offer with the lowest price or if the tender is to be cancelled.
There are no regulations in the Czech Republic.
