For the construction services, it was often not clear whether the offers of freelancers were only accessible to those directly involved in the processing.
Review and calculation of the offers
Some contracting authorities handed over the open offers to freelancers for further examination, without having previously carried out the prescribed review of the offers and the computational examination itself, and without having reviewed their results.
In the event of manipulative intentions, third parties could have made changes to the offers without this being comprehensible to the contracting authorities.
In the audited documents, anomalies or missing price or product information were partly not or only insufficiently marked.
Performance audits
On a sample in a building Services Administration, the most favourable offers in three quarters of the audited procurement procedures deviated more than 10% from the previously determined estimated costs.
One in 20 procurement procedures has been overturned because of inappropriate offer prices.
Not all offers and information discussions with the bidders were comprehensible or sufficiently documented.
In many cases, there was a lack of further information, such as on the uniform prices of the most important positions.
Frequently, the deviations were only justified on a blanket basis, e.g. by indications of changed market prices or increased material costs.
The Construction Services said it was difficult to detect and prove mixed calculations.
In the case of an invitation to tender by an institution under public law, the offer price of the cheapest offer was 66% below the previously determined estimate of these services.
Detailed calculations or investigations into the causes of this deviation were not documented.
In a briefing, the registry found no evidence of price dumping by the company that was then commissioned.
This left it unclear whether the estimated value was excessive or whether the offer price was too low.
Later, the client assessed the commissioned company as a "low-cost company," which could not keep quality or deadlines.
In another tender, a construction agency awarded the contract to an offer whose price was 35% higher than the value of the cost calculation.
She did not cancel the tender, citing the non-factual reasoning that this company could conclude on an adequate calculation.
Suspicions of irregularities
There were two cases of irregularities in an audited Building Administration, both of which were reported to the specialist Inspectorate.
In one of the cases, the calculation of two bidders was identical in a tender, so that the contracting authority excluded both bids from the procedure.
In the application of the remaining regulations, the tests did not give rise to any significant objections.
