Aptitude test
For many of the construction projects tested, including university construction, road construction and rail network expansion, the contracting authorities did not exclude bidders from the procedure, even though they did not meet the requirements specified in the tender documents or were unable to prove their suitability to the prescribed extent. On the other hand, in one case, a contracting authority could neither prove nor explain why it had excluded a bidder who had fulfilled the requirements.
Standings
When awarding construction services for a water treatment plant, the contracting authority did not take into account the specified evaluation criteria when examining and evaluating the tenders.
In the case of a construction project to expand the rail network, the awarding authority only determined the weighting of the evaluation criteria at the beginning of the evaluation.
In the case of road maintenance measures, the predetermined criterion of "shortening the construction phase" was misjudged in a procedure.
As a result, the offered reduction was insufficiently taken into account by the bidders in second and third positions.
Documentation of the selection of offers
The registry did not document the criteria it had applied and the basis on which it had selected the successful bidder for three procurement procedures in the context of the Housing Promotion.
In the construction of a motorway, the contracting authority selected the companies for smaller orders up to 20,000 euros on the basis of telephone surveys on Prices and Terms of Delivery.
Tests of this selection were not possible, as the surveys were not documented.
Summary findings
The rules for the examination and evaluation of offers in both countries are in line with the requirements of the EU.
However, in the case of details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective regulations differ from one another.
In Germany, the procedure is more regulated than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, in particular for the implementation of the multi-eyes principle and for the protection of offers.
The same applies to the requirements on the basis of which the appropriateness of the offered prices has to be checked.
In both countries, some of the audited procurement procedures have found that significant procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of bids have not been documented, or have not been sufficiently documented.
Without comprehensibility and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions, however, possible manipulative interventions are favored.
A particularly serious shortcoming was the handing over of all offers to third parties, without the contracting authority having previously sufficiently looked through and documented the offers and thus protected them from possible manipulation in the further proceedings.
If contracting authorities have tasks done by third parties in the examination and evaluation of the offers, sufficient precautions and an increased expenditure of control are necessary in order to counter the increased risk of manipulation.
When assessing the appropriateness of prices, the services audited in Germany did not always make full use of the set of instruments and did not sufficiently examine the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, there have been complaints, especially regarding the aptitude test and the application of the evaluation criteria.
Completion of the award procedure
After examination and evaluation of the bids, the award procedure will be concluded by awarding the award or by cancelling the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all bidders must be informed in advance of the proposed award decision.
The companies have the possibility to examine the intended Award in the case of information by electronic means or by fax within 10 days or in the case of other means of communication within 15 days and, if necessary, to initiate a review procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the end of this information period.
