In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the bidder's offer in terms of content in the contract.
In the case of some contracts, such as road maintenance works, the construction of a motorway and a bypass, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts after expiry of the legal deadline.
When awarding construction services for the renovation of former military sites, the contracting authority only forwarded the notification of the award to all bidders after the legal deadline.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the EU requirements for the completion of the award procedure.
The legal protection of unsuccessful applicants or bidders will increase the tools for preventing corruption.
The scope of legal protection in Czech Public Procurement Law has also been extended to contracts below the EU thresholds.
In both countries, the deadlines for placing the order have been exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
In the future, the building authorities should avoid the shortcomings identified in the completion of their procurement procedures.
Documentation, reporting and reporting requirements
The award procedures must be documented in a comprehensible manner during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings and the justifications of the individual decisions.
For EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made public.
The order data is also recorded in an EU statistic.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption through the documentation of procurement procedures are implemented as a basic requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.
A meticulous and timely documentation only makes it possible to track the award decisions.
In particular, it also provides effective legal protection for bidders in contracts above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the obligation to explain award decisions in detail reduces the scope for manipulation.
The publication of a contract awarded in an EU-wide tender procedure has to be submitted by the respective contracting authority to the Office for Official Publications of the EU within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU, thus also implementing the transparency requirement.
The contracting authorities must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the relevant national ministries of the EU Commission.
On this basis, the European Commission draws up an annual EU statistics to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Regulations of German and Czech Public Procurement Law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully implemented the EU's documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Diverging regulations
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish awarded contracts is not only limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.
The notice period is shortened to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide contracts, there is a publishing obligation only for limited tenders and for free-handed contracts with value limits of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these limits, as well as in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition process will receive information on the award of contracts.
