Summary evaluation and Recommendations
The parallel tests of the ncú and the BRH have focused on two priorities, which are essential in the Czech Republic and in Germany for the award of construction services by public authorities: the application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law allow for cross-border competition to create a European single market.
Anti-corruption measures serve not only to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and a possible loss of trust in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two courts of auditors on the application of the public procurement rules in both countries, as well as the comparison of these regulations, reveal similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their public procurement law and its application.
Application of EU public procurement rules
The EU's requirements for the award of construction services have been transposed into national law by both countries.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and in Germany, there is an important common basis for the award of construction services and the consideration of the essential requirements of competition, the equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of procurement procedures.
The building authorities of both countries have partially subjected these bids to extensive administrative regulations.
The Czech Republic has also largely transferred the requirements for the construction services to be awarded across the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the investigations carried out by the courts of auditors have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The Building Administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to remove the objections raised when implementing the EU requirements.
The tests in the Czech Republic have shown, above all, dangers that affect the profitability of the awards.
For example, incomplete performance descriptions required additional services, which were often awarded in breach of legislation, and cost assessments were usually insufficiently prepared, and excessive qualification requirements reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the transport sector.
Prevention of corruption
The investigations have not had the aim of uncovering corruption cases,
It is also because the courts of auditors do not have the appropriate instruments to do so.
The courts of auditors can, however, examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of construction services and how these requirements are applied.
In the prevention of corruption, both countries have set different priorities.
Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition and transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.
The Czech regulations are primarily aimed at increasing the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of the prevention of corruption, which the entire federal administration has to apply, apply.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared to their specific requirements.
In some cases, the relevant regulations stipulate very precisely how the bids for preventing corruption should be taken into account in the course of the procurement procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In the BRH's view, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tender in particular is a suitable instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the award of construction works, while restrictions on competition increase the risk of manipulative intervention.
Risk analyses and sufficient controls (especially the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures, as well as various organisational measures, are also effective measures to prevent corruption and manipulation.
The BRH therefore does not see any fundamental need for changes to the corresponding requirements of the administrations in the award of construction services.
The rules on preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some of the benchmarks.
The building authorities should continue to train their employees on the guidelines for preventing corruption and make them even more aware of this problem.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks delegated by the building authorities to freelancers.
However, without controls and sufficient safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.
Therefore, tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against illegal interference.
Nkú
At government level, the Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption, in which public procurement is the most important element.
The Procurement Act and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The ncú audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions are likely to be effective improvement measures, as the contracting authorities have to justify the cost-effectiveness of the contracts, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the type of evaluations, and properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The ncú and the BRH assess the implementation of the EU requirements in a fundamentally positive way.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's requirements of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for awarding construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects to enable and promote cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and ideal damage potential caused by manipulation and corruption in the awarding of construction services, both courts of auditors see the building authorities in their countries as being required to continue and, if necessary, to improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
A greater division of construction services into lots can also have a favourable effect on offer prices, provided that this results in greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient contracting of public authorities.
In Germany, procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised Building Authorities, whereas in the Czech Republic, these tasks - with the exception of transport projects - are carried out by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.
The courts of auditors of both countries have the intention to continue to develop the relevant findings and, if necessary, to bring them to the attention of the Parliament and the government of their country, even after the completion of their joint project.
Both courts of auditors also believe that the principles of public procurement law and its implementation, set out in this report, are of interest to the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles and findings set out are of general importance for effectively countering corruption and ensuring the economic award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
